What is a Mint Mark?

A mint mark is a small letter stamped on a coin that tells you where it was made:

  • D = Denver Mint
  • S = San Francisco Mint
  • (No mark) = Philadelphia Mint (in 1944, Philly coins had no letter)

On the Mercury Dime:

The mint mark is located on the reverse (back) side of the coin the side you just photographed to the right of the bottom of the torch, just left of the word ONE and above DIME.

In your photo:

It looks like there is no mint mark, which means your 1944 dime was struck in Philadelphia.

Want to Know Its Value?

Because it's a common date from the Philadelphia Mint and well circulated, its main value is in silver roughly $2 to $4, but that can go up depending on silver prices or if it's part of a collector set.
